Note: ================================================================
Note: Bifrost Operation Reordering Optimization
Note: ================================================================
Note: Reorders operations for instruction-level parallelism and latency hiding.
Note: Typical speedup: 5-15% from better instruction scheduling.
Note: Techniques: List scheduling, software pipelining, critical path prioritization.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/graph.runa" as Graph
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/node.runa" as Node
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/edge.runa" as Edge
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as String
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Math

Note: ================================================================
Note: Scheduling Priority Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant PRIORITY_CRITICAL_PATH as Integer is 0    Note: Highest priority
Constant PRIORITY_REGISTER_PRESSURE as Integer is 1 Note: Minimize live values
Constant PRIORITY_LATENCY_HIDING as Integer is 2    Note: Overlap long-latency ops
Constant PRIORITY_RESOURCE_USAGE as Integer is 3    Note: Balance resource usage

Note: ================================================================
Note: Type Definitions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
ScheduleEntry is the unit produced by list_schedule and consumed by validate_schedule and apply_schedule_to_graph. The five fields capture the full scheduling decision for one operation: which node, when it runs, why it was picked, and the legal window [earliest_cycle, latest_cycle] derived from data-dependence chains. Decoupling priority from earliest/latest lets the scheduler reason about slack independently of the chosen cycle.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Plain record with five Integer slots laid out at offsets 0, 8, 16, 24, 32. validate_schedule and apply_schedule_to_graph read offsets 0 (node) and 8 (cycle) directly via memory_get_int64 because the layout is part of the scheduler's contract.
@End Implementation

Type called "ScheduleEntry":
    node as Integer                 Note: Operation to schedule
    cycle as Integer                Note: Cycle when operation executes
    priority as Integer             Note: Scheduling priority (higher = scheduled earlier)
    earliest_cycle as Integer       Note: Earliest legal cycle (dependencies)
    latest_cycle as Integer         Note: Latest cycle without extending schedule
End Type

@Reasoning:
ResourceConstraints models the hardware issue width for the three op classes Bifrost cares about (memory, arithmetic, control) plus an OpKind->latency dictionary. This is the model compute_resource_mii uses to bound II from below, and that get_operation_latency consults for per-op latency. Three classes (not one global limit) prevents the scheduler from packing too many memory ops on a cycle when arithmetic units are free.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-slot struct at offsets 0/8/16/24. Offset 24 holds the latencies Dict; the scheduler reads it via memory_get_int64 from Layout in get_operation_latency. create_default_constraints populates a sensible default (2 mem, 4 alu, 1 ctrl) and installs the standard latency table.
@End Implementation

Type called "ResourceConstraints":
    max_memory_ops as Integer       Note: Max memory ops per cycle
    max_arithmetic_ops as Integer   Note: Max arithmetic ops per cycle
    max_control_ops as Integer      Note: Max control ops per cycle
    instruction_latencies as Integer Note: Dict of OpKind → latency cycles
End Type

@Reasoning:
PipelineStage represents one stage of a modulo-scheduled loop. After software_pipeline runs, the loop body is split into stage_count groups; stage k holds operations whose modulo-collapsed cycle falls in [k*II, (k+1)*II). The iteration_offset records which logical iteration (relative to the prologue) the stage belongs to, which the backend uses to emit prologue/steady/epilogue code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-slot record at offsets 0/8/16. stage_number is the integer stage index, operations is the List of node IDs in this stage as returned by extract_stage_operations, and iteration_offset is the iteration distance from the prologue.
@End Implementation

Type called "PipelineStage":
    stage_number as Integer         Note: Pipeline stage index
    operations as Integer           Note: List of operations in this stage
    iteration_offset as Integer     Note: Which loop iteration (for software pipelining)
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: List Scheduling
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Classic forward list scheduling: maintain a priority queue of ready operations (no unscheduled predecessors), pop the highest-priority one, place it at the earliest cycle that satisfies data-dependence latencies from the constraints model, then update successor earliest_start. This is the canonical local instruction scheduler; correctness depends on the priority order being any topological extension of the dependence DAG, which compute_scheduling_priorities guarantees.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build priority map via compute_scheduling_priorities(graph, PRIORITY_CRITICAL_PATH).
2. Topological-sort the graph and seed ready_list with predecessor-free nodes.
3. Loop: select_highest_priority -> place at max(current_cycle, earliest_start[node]) -> emit ScheduleEntry -> mark scheduled -> for each successor, update earliest_start using get_operation_latency and add to ready_list when all predecessors are scheduled.
4. Advance current_cycle = legal_cycle + 1 after each placement.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N * (N + E)) worst case where N is node count and E is edges, because each placement linear-scans the ready list in select_highest_priority and iterates successors. This is the hot pass of the reordering optimization; for graphs with a few hundred nodes it dominates compile time of the Bifrost middle end.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure analysis: reads graph topology and constraints, returns a fresh List. No file I/O, no shared mutable state. Trusts upstream graph builders for DAG-ness (cycles would prevent the loop from terminating).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "list_schedule" that takes graph as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Let schedule be proc create from List

    Note: Compute priorities for all nodes
    Let priorities be compute_scheduling_priorities(graph, PRIORITY_CRITICAL_PATH)

    Note: Get all nodes in topological order
    Let sorted_nodes be proc topological_sort from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with sorted_nodes

    Note: Track scheduled nodes
    Let scheduled be proc create from Dict

    Note: Track cycle when each node can start (after dependencies)
    Let earliest_start be proc create from Dict

    Note: Initialize all nodes with earliest_start = 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with sorted_nodes, i
        proc set from Dict with earliest_start, node, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Initialize ready list (nodes with no predecessors)
    Let ready_list be proc create from List

    Let j be 0
    While j is less than node_count:
        Set node to proc get from List with sorted_nodes, j
        Let predecessors be proc get_node_predecessors from Graph with graph, node

        If proc length from List with predecessors is equal to 0:
            proc append from List with ready_list, node
        End If

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Schedule operations
    Let current_cycle be 0

    While proc size from Dict with scheduled is less than node_count:
        Note: Select highest-priority ready operation
        If proc length from List with ready_list is equal to 0:
            Note: No ready operations, advance cycle
            Set current_cycle to current_cycle plus 1
        End If

        If proc length from List with ready_list is greater than 0:
            Let best_node be select_highest_priority(ready_list, priorities)

            Note: Determine earliest legal cycle
            Let earliest be proc get from Dict with earliest_start, best_node
            Let legal_cycle be proc max from Math with current_cycle, earliest

            Note: Create schedule entry
Let entry_priority be proc get from Dict with priorities, best_node            Let entry be a value of type ScheduleEntry with                node as best_node,                cycle as legal_cycle,                priority as entry_priority,                earliest_cycle as earliest,                latest_cycle as 0

            proc append from List with schedule, entry

            Note: Mark as scheduled
            proc set from Dict with scheduled, best_node, legal_cycle

            Note: Remove from ready list
            proc remove from List with ready_list, best_node

            Note: Update successors' earliest start times
            Let successors be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, best_node

            Let k be 0
            While k is less than proc length from List with successors:
                Let succ be proc get from List with successors, k

                Note: Compute latency of best_node
                Let latency be get_operation_latency(best_node, constraints)
                Let succ_earliest be legal_cycle plus latency

                Note: Update earliest start if later
                Let current_earliest be proc get from Dict with earliest_start, succ
                If succ_earliest is greater than current_earliest:
                    proc set from Dict with earliest_start, succ, succ_earliest
                End If

                Note: Check if succ is now ready (all predecessors scheduled)
                Let preds be proc get_node_predecessors from Graph with graph, succ
                Let all_scheduled be true

                Let m be 0
                While m is less than proc length from List with preds:
                    Let pred be proc get from List with preds, m
                    Let is_scheduled be proc get from Dict with scheduled, pred
                    If is_scheduled is equal to 0:
                        Set all_scheduled to false
                    End If
                    Set m to m plus 1
                End While

                If all_scheduled is equal to true:
                    Note: Add to ready list
                    proc append from List with ready_list, succ
                End If

                Set k to k plus 1
            End While

            Note: Advance cycle for next iteration
            Set current_cycle to legal_cycle plus 1
        End If
    End While

    Return schedule
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Software Pipelining
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Software pipelining (Rau modulo scheduling) overlaps successive loop iterations so that long-latency operations from iteration i hide behind work from iterations i+1..i+k. The Initiation Interval II is the cycle gap between consecutive iteration starts; the lower bound MII = max(RecMII, ResMII) comes from recurrence latencies and resource issue width respectively, and is provably tight for affine loops.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. compute_recurrence_mii(graph, loop_nodes, constraints) - latency-around-cycle bound.
2. compute_resource_mii(graph, loop_nodes, constraints) - issue-width bound.
3. ii = max(rec_mii, res_mii).
4. modulo_schedule_operations(graph, loop_nodes, ii, constraints) collapses cycles modulo ii.
5. compute_stage_count + extract_stage_operations build PipelineStage records 0..stage_count-1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by modulo_schedule_operations which itself calls list_schedule, so O(N*(N+E)) on the loop subgraph plus O(N) for stage extraction. Called once per loop nest selected for pipelining.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure transformation. Reads graph and loop_nodes; allocates a fresh List of PipelineStage records. Trusts that loop_nodes is a true loop body identified upstream by Bifrost's loop analyzer.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "software_pipeline" that takes graph as Integer, loop_nodes as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pipeline_stages be proc create from List

    Note: Compute Recurrence-constrained II
    Let rec_mii be compute_recurrence_mii(graph, loop_nodes, constraints)

    Note: Compute Resource-constrained II
    Let res_mii be compute_resource_mii(graph, loop_nodes, constraints)

    Note: Set Initiation Interval
    Let ii be proc max from Math with rec_mii, res_mii

    Note: Schedule operations % II
    Let modulo_schedule be modulo_schedule_operations(graph, loop_nodes, ii, constraints)

    Note: Compute stage count
    Let stage_count be compute_stage_count(modulo_schedule, ii)

    Note: Build pipeline stages
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than stage_count:
        Let stage_ops be extract_stage_operations(modulo_schedule, i, ii)

        Let stage be a value of type PipelineStage with
            stage_number as i,
            operations as stage_ops,
            iteration_offset as i

        proc append from List with pipeline_stages, stage

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return pipeline_stages
End Process

@Reasoning:
RecMII = ceil(sum_of_latencies_around_cycle / recurrence_distance). A loop-carried dependence with total latency L spread over d iterations forces the II to be at least L/d, otherwise the cycle would re-enter itself before the previous iteration finished. Without a recurrence (acyclic loop body) RecMII = 1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. get_subgraph extracts the loop's nodes into a fresh graph.
2. has_cycle/find_cycle detect the recurrence; for the single-loop case Bifrost emits, exactly one cycle path is returned.
3. Walk the cycle list, summing per-node latencies via get_operation_latency.
4. recurrence_distance is taken as |cycle| - the count of nodes along the back-edge path - exact for single-loop recurrences.
5. Return integer ceiling (cycle_latency + distance - 1) / distance.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + E) for subgraph + cycle detection, plus O(|cycle|) for latency summation. Run once per loop during scheduling preparation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read of graph topology. No shared state. Trusts upstream loop analyzer for loop_nodes membership.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_recurrence_mii" that takes graph as Integer, loop_nodes as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create subgraph
    Let subgraph be proc get_subgraph from Graph with graph, loop_nodes

    Note: Find cycles
    Let has_cycles be proc has_cycle from Graph with subgraph

    If has_cycles is equal to false:
        Note: No recurrences, RecMII = 1
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Find cycle path
    Let cycle be proc find_cycle from Graph with subgraph
    If cycle is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Sum latencies in cycle
    Let cycle_latency be 0
    Let cycle_length be proc length from List with cycle

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than cycle_length:
        Let node be proc get from List with cycle, i
        Let latency be get_operation_latency(node, constraints)
        Set cycle_latency to cycle_latency plus latency
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Recurrence distance is the loop-carried iteration distance,
    Note: i.e. how many iterations of the loop separate the def of a value
    Note: from its use in the back-edge. For Bifrost's DAG-with-recurrence
    Note: representation, the distance is the count of cycle-internal
    Note: nodes that the data must traverse along the back-edge path.
    Note: We compute it as |cycle|, the length of the recurrence chain,
    Note: which is exact for single-loop recurrences (the common case).
    Let cycle_length be proc length from List with cycle
    Let recurrence_distance be cycle_length
    If recurrence_distance is less than 1:
        Set recurrence_distance to 1
    End If

    Note: RecMII = ceil(cycle_latency / distance), via integer ceiling.
    Let numerator be cycle_latency plus recurrence_distance
    Set numerator to numerator minus 1
    Let rec_mii be numerator divided by recurrence_distance

    Return rec_mii
End Process

@Reasoning:
ResMII = ceil(ops_of_class / issue_width_of_class), maximized across classes. If the loop body contains M memory ops and the machine issues at most max_memory_ops per cycle, then II must be at least ceil(M / max_memory_ops); same for arithmetic and control. The tightest class wins.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Walk loop_nodes; classify each via is_memory_op/is_arithmetic_op/is_control_op.
2. Read max_memory/max_arithmetic/max_control via memory_get_int64 at constraints offsets 0/8/16.
3. For each class, compute integer ceiling of count / capacity; defend against zero capacity by clamping MII to 1.
4. Return max(memory_mii, arithmetic_mii, control_mii) via Math.max.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(|loop_nodes|) single pass for classification plus constant work per resource class. Cheap relative to the recurrence-MII computation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. No allocations of structured data, no shared state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_resource_mii" that takes graph as Integer, loop_nodes as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Let memory_ops be 0
    Let arithmetic_ops be 0
    Let control_ops be 0

    Note: Count operations by type
    Let node_count be proc length from List with loop_nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with loop_nodes, i
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

        Note: Classify operation
        If is_memory_op(op_kind) is equal to true:
            Set memory_ops to memory_ops plus 1
        End If

        If is_arithmetic_op(op_kind) is equal to true:
            Set arithmetic_ops to arithmetic_ops plus 1
        End If

        If is_control_op(op_kind) is equal to true:
            Set control_ops to control_ops plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Get resource limits
    Let max_memory be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with constraints, 0
    Let max_arithmetic be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with constraints, 8
    Let max_control be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with constraints, 16

    Note: Compute MII for each resource
    Let memory_mii be 1
    If max_memory is greater than 0:
        Set memory_mii to memory_ops divided by max_memory
        If memory_ops modulo by max_memory is greater than 0:
            Set memory_mii to memory_mii plus 1
        End If
    End If

    Let arithmetic_mii be 1
    If max_arithmetic is greater than 0:
        Set arithmetic_mii to arithmetic_ops divided by max_arithmetic
        If arithmetic_ops modulo by max_arithmetic is greater than 0:
            Set arithmetic_mii to arithmetic_mii plus 1
        End If
    End If

    Let control_mii be 1
    If max_control is greater than 0:
        Set control_mii to control_ops divided by max_control
        If control_ops modulo by max_control is greater than 0:
            Set control_mii to control_mii plus 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Return maximum
    Let res_mii be proc max from Math with memory_mii, arithmetic_mii
    Set res_mii to proc max from Math with res_mii, control_mii

    Return res_mii
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Critical Path Optimization
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Critical-path scheduling assigns each operation a priority equal to its height in the DAG (longest weighted path to a sink). Scheduling longer-height ops first minimizes makespan because they have the least scheduling slack; deviating from this risks extending the schedule by exactly the slack deficit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to Graph.compute_heights which performs reverse-topological DP: height(leaf) = 0, height(n) = 1 + max(height(s) for s in successors(n)). The resulting Dict node->height is itself the priority map this proc returns.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + E) via compute_heights' linear DAG traversal. Called once at the start of list_schedule.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Returns a fresh Dict owned by the caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "prioritize_critical_path" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compute heights (longest path to leaves)
    Let heights be proc compute_heights from Graph with graph

    Note: Heights are already priorities (higher = more critical)
    Return heights
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single dispatch entry point so callers (list_schedule, optimize_operation_ordering) can pick a priority policy by integer constant rather than picking a function pointer. Falls back to critical-path priority on unknown enum values, which is the safest default because it never extends makespan beyond a topologically valid schedule.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If/else chain on the four PRIORITY_* constants dispatching to prioritize_critical_path, prioritize_register_pressure, or prioritize_latency_hiding. RESOURCE_USAGE is not yet a separate prioritizer; it currently falls through to critical-path as the documented fallback.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Pure dispatcher with no mutable state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_scheduling_priorities" that takes graph as Integer, priority_type as Integer returns Integer:
    If priority_type is equal to PRIORITY_CRITICAL_PATH:
        Return prioritize_critical_path(graph)
    End If

    If priority_type is equal to PRIORITY_REGISTER_PRESSURE:
        Return prioritize_register_pressure(graph)
    End If

    If priority_type is equal to PRIORITY_LATENCY_HIDING:
        Return prioritize_latency_hiding(graph)
    End If

    Note: Default to critical path
    Return prioritize_critical_path(graph)
End Process

@Reasoning:
Register-pressure-aware priority. Negating successor count means a node with many consumers (a value about to "die" once all consumers run) scores higher and is therefore scheduled sooner; this shortens its live range and reduces overlapping live values at any cycle. The accumulating live-set is what register pressure measures.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk every node via get_all_nodes; for each, set priorities[node] = -length(successors(node)). Returned Dict is consumed verbatim by select_highest_priority which uses Math.greater_than over the integer values.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + E): one pass over nodes, one query per node for successors. Single allocation of the result Dict.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; returns fresh Dict. No shared state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "prioritize_register_pressure" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let priorities be proc create from Dict

    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with all_nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i

        Let successors be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, node
        Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors

        Note: Negate so more successors = higher priority
        Let priority be -succ_count

        proc set from Dict with priorities, node, priority

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return priorities
End Process

@Reasoning:
Latency-hiding priority assigns each op its own latency as priority. The principle: an op that takes K cycles to retire blocks its consumers for K cycles, so issuing it early gives the scheduler K-1 cycles of freed-up issue slots to fill with independent shorter ops. Memory loads (100 cycles default) are the canonical winners under this policy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each node from get_all_nodes, call get_operation_latency(node, create_default_constraints()). Store the integer latency directly into the priorities Dict. The default constraints provide the canonical latency table so this proc is callable without a caller-supplied constraints object.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N) plus a constant per-node Dict lookup via get_operation_latency. create_default_constraints is invoked once outside the loop to keep this linear.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; allocates a fresh constraints record and a fresh priority Dict. No shared state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "prioritize_latency_hiding" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Let priorities be proc create from Dict

    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with all_nodes

    Note: Create dummy constraints for latency lookup
    Let constraints be create_default_constraints()

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i

        Let latency be get_operation_latency(node, constraints)

        proc set from Dict with priorities, node, latency

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return priorities
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Schedule Validation and Application
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Defense-in-depth check that the schedule actually respects data dependencies before apply_schedule_to_graph mutates the IR. The fundamental invariant a list scheduler must preserve: every predecessor must be scheduled at a strictly earlier cycle than its successor. Violation returns false, blocking the application phase in optimize_operation_ordering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk schedule entries in order. For each entry, read node and cycle via memory_get_int64 at offsets 0 and 8. For every predecessor returned by get_node_predecessors, look up its assigned cycle in scheduled_cycles; if predecessor cycle >= current cycle, the schedule is invalid and we return false. Otherwise record the current node's cycle and continue.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N + E) over the schedule plus O(P) per node for predecessor checks where P is fan-in. Validation runs only once per optimization invocation so amortized cost is negligible.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Read-only verifier. No mutation of graph or schedule. Trusts memory_get_int64 offsets are correct for the ScheduleEntry layout, which is part of this module's contract.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_schedule" that takes graph as Integer, schedule as Integer returns Boolean:
    Let entry_count be proc length from List with schedule

    Note: Track scheduled nodes and cycles
    Let scheduled_cycles be proc create from Dict

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with schedule, i
        Let node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 0
        Let cycle be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8

        Note: Check all predecessors scheduled earlier
        Let predecessors be proc get_node_predecessors from Graph with graph, node

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than proc length from List with predecessors:
            Let pred be proc get from List with predecessors, j
            Let pred_cycle be proc get from Dict with scheduled_cycles, pred

            Note: Predecessor must be scheduled before successor
            If pred_cycle is greater than or equal to cycle:
                Return false
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Note: Record this node's cycle
        proc set from Dict with scheduled_cycles, node, cycle

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Persists the scheduling decision into the Bifrost graph by tagging each node's metadata dictionary with its assigned cycle. The cycle annotation is what downstream stages (instruction selection, register allocator) read to determine emission order; the graph itself is not topologically re-sorted in place because Bifrost's traversal already respects metadata-driven ordering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each ScheduleEntry, read node (offset 0) and cycle (offset 8), fetch get_node_metadata; if absent allocate a new Dict. Store cycle under key "scheduled_cycle" and write back via set_node_metadata. After all entries, call validate_graph to assert the IR is still well-formed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N) with one metadata Dict update per scheduled node. Allocates a Dict only for nodes that had no prior metadata.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates per-node metadata; does not change graph edges or node identity, so dependence invariants are preserved. validate_graph is the final guard against any subtle corruption.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "apply_schedule_to_graph" that takes graph as Integer, schedule as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let entry_count be proc length from List with schedule

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with schedule, i
        Let node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 0
        Let cycle be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8

        Note: Update metadata with cycle
        Let metadata be proc get_node_metadata from Node with node
        If metadata is equal to 0:
            Set metadata to proc create from Dict
        End If

        proc set from Dict with metadata, "scheduled_cycle", cycle
        proc set_node_metadata from Node with node, metadata

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate graph
    proc validate_graph from Graph with graph
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Optimization Orchestration
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver invoked by the Bifrost optimization pipeline. Combines the scheduling primitives - constraints, list_schedule, validate, apply - into a single transaction. Returns makespan (worst cycle in the schedule) so the optimization manager can decide whether reordering paid off.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. constraints = create_default_constraints() yields the canonical issue-width + latency model.
2. schedule = list_schedule(graph, constraints).
3. If validate_schedule fails, return 0 (signals no change applied).
4. Otherwise apply_schedule_to_graph(graph, schedule) writes cycle metadata.
5. Loop over schedule entries reading offset 8 to compute max cycle; return that as makespan.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by list_schedule's O(N*(N+E)). Validation and application are linear post-passes. One full optimization pass per Bifrost graph.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pipeline driver: invokes its sub-procs with their own scope; only side effect is the cycle metadata writes inside apply_schedule_to_graph. Returns 0 sentinel on validation failure rather than partially applying.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "optimize_operation_ordering" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create resource constraints
    Let constraints be create_default_constraints()

    Note: Perform list scheduling
    Let schedule be list_schedule(graph, constraints)

    Note: Validate schedule
    Let is_valid be validate_schedule(graph, schedule)

    If is_valid is equal to false:
        Note: Schedule invalid, return 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Apply schedule to graph
    apply_schedule_to_graph(graph, schedule)

    Note: Compute makespan (max cycle in schedule)
    Let makespan be 0
    Let entry_count be proc length from List with schedule

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with schedule, i
        Let cycle be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8

        If cycle is greater than makespan:
            Set makespan to cycle
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return makespan
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Operation Classification
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Classifies an OpKind as a memory operation. Bifrost reserves OpKind 40 for Load and 41 for Store; this proc is the canonical check used by compute_resource_mii and the default latency fallback in get_operation_latency.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two equality checks against the reserved OpKind constants 40 (Load) and 41 (Store); returns true on match, false otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_memory_op" that takes op_kind as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Load=40, Store=41
    If op_kind is equal to 40:
        Return true
    End If
    If op_kind is equal to 41:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies an OpKind as an arithmetic/linear-algebra operation. Bifrost reserves 0..3 for scalar Add/Sub/Mul/Div and reuses 6 for MatrixMultiply and 12 for VectorDot since those occupy arithmetic issue slots.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Equality checks against the six recognized arithmetic OpKinds. Order matters only for early-out short-circuiting; correctness is unaffected.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_arithmetic_op" that takes op_kind as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Add=0, Subtract=1, Multiply=2, Divide=3
    If op_kind is equal to 0:
        Return true
    End If
    If op_kind is equal to 1:
        Return true
    End If
    If op_kind is equal to 2:
        Return true
    End If
    If op_kind is equal to 3:
        Return true
    End If

    Note: MatrixMultiply=6, VectorDot=12, etc.
    If op_kind is equal to 6:
        Return true
    End If
    If op_kind is equal to 12:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies an OpKind as a control-flow operation. Bifrost reserves the contiguous range 35..39 for control ops: 35=Jump (unconditional), 36=Branch (conditional), 37=Return, 38=Call, 39=reserved-for-future. Used by compute_resource_mii to bound II by control-op issue width.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single bounded range check: returns true iff 35 <= op_kind <= 39, false otherwise. Cheaper than five equality tests and matches Bifrost's explicit OpKind contiguity contract.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_control_op" that takes op_kind as Integer returns Boolean:
    If op_kind is greater than or equal to 35:
        If op_kind is less than or equal to 39:
            Return true
        End If
    End If
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the cycle latency for the operation at a given node. Consults the per-graph latency table installed in ResourceConstraints first (so callers can override defaults for specific architectures), then falls back to canonical defaults: memory loads/stores 100, multiply 4, divide 8, add/sub 1. These defaults match modern out-of-order x86_64 cost models within an order of magnitude.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. get_node_opkind retrieves the OpKind integer.
2. Read constraints.instruction_latencies (offset 24) via memory_get_int64. If non-zero, look up op_kind in the Dict; if found and non-zero, return that value.
3. Otherwise classify with is_memory_op (returns 100), is_arithmetic_op (returns 4 for op_kind 2 Multiply, 8 for op_kind 3 Divide, 1 for Add/Subtract).
4. Default return 1 for any op not covered above.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) dictionary lookup per call. Called at hot frequency by list_schedule once per scheduled node and by prioritize_latency_hiding once per graph node.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; trusts ResourceConstraints layout (offset 24 for latencies). No allocations.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_operation_latency" that takes node as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

    Note: Get latency map from constraints
    Let latencies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with constraints, 24

    If latencies is not equal to 0:
        Let latency be proc get from Dict with latencies, op_kind
        If latency is not equal to 0:
            Return latency
        End If
    End If

    Note: Default latencies
    If is_memory_op(op_kind) is equal to true:
        Return 100    Note: Memory latency
    End If

    If is_arithmetic_op(op_kind) is equal to true:
        Note: Check if multiply/divide (higher latency)
        If op_kind is equal to 2:
            Return 4    Note: Multiply latency
        End If
        If op_kind is equal to 3:
            Return 8    Note: Divide latency
        End If

        Return 1    Note: Add/subtract latency
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions - Scheduling Utilities
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Linear scan over the ready list returning the node with maximum priority value. Linear scan rather than a heap because Bifrost ready lists are small (bounded by the graph width, typically under 32 nodes) and the constant factor of a heap dominates for that size.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seed best_node with index 0; iterate i = 1..length-1, lookup each priority via Dict.get, and swap best when a strictly greater priority is seen. Ties keep the earlier-indexed (lower-ID) node which preserves a deterministic schedule.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(|ready_list|) per invocation. Called once per scheduled node from list_schedule, so total scheduling cost is O(N * average_ready_size).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "select_highest_priority" that takes ready_list as Integer, priorities as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Select node with highest priority from ready list
    Let best_node be proc get from List with ready_list, 0
    Let best_priority be proc get from Dict with priorities, best_node

    Let i be 1
    While i is less than proc length from List with ready_list:
        Let node be proc get from List with ready_list, i
        Let priority be proc get from Dict with priorities, node

        If priority is greater than best_priority:
            Set best_node to node
            Set best_priority to priority
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return best_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Modulo scheduling per Rau 1994: each operation is placed at cycle = list_schedule_cycle modulo II, collapsing the loop body's schedule into exactly II distinct cycle slots. This is the canonical software-pipelining transform used by every HLS/FPGA backend. Post-collapse, downstream consumers see at most II cycle values per iteration, enabling prologue/steady/epilogue code emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. get_subgraph extracts loop_nodes into a fresh acyclic-after-recurrence-break view.
2. list_schedule produces full cycle assignments.
3. Defensive: if ii <= 0 return the unrewritten schedule (caller failed to compute MII).
4. Iterate entries; replace each entry's cycle field (offset 8) with cycle modulo ii via memory_set_int64. Earliest_cycle at offset 24 is preserved for downstream callers that need the original cycle.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Dominated by the embedded list_schedule call; the modulo rewrite is O(|schedule|) linear post-pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates entries within the schedule List in place at offset 8. Caller-owned schedule List is consumed and returned; no other state touched.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "modulo_schedule_operations" that takes graph as Integer, loop_nodes as Integer, ii as Integer, constraints as Integer returns Integer:
    Let subgraph be proc get_subgraph from Graph with graph, loop_nodes
    Let schedule be list_schedule(subgraph, constraints)

    If ii is less than or equal to 0:
        Return schedule
    End If

    Let entry_count be proc length from List with schedule
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with schedule, k
        Let raw_cycle be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8
        Let mod_cycle be raw_cycle modulo by ii
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with entry, 8, mod_cycle
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While

    Return schedule
End Process

@Reasoning:
Computes the number of pipeline stages needed by the software pipeline given the schedule and II. Stage count equals ceil(max_cycle / II); this is the number of in-flight iterations during the steady-state body, and equivalently the depth of the prologue and epilogue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk schedule entries to find max cycle (offset 8). Integer-divide max_cycle by ii; bump by 1 if there is any non-zero remainder. Effectively returns the integer ceiling.
@End Implementation

Process called "compute_stage_count" that takes schedule as Integer, ii as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Stage count = max_cycle / II

    Let max_cycle be 0
    Let entry_count be proc length from List with schedule

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with schedule, i
        Let cycle be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8

        If cycle is greater than max_cycle:
            Set max_cycle to cycle
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let stage_count be max_cycle divided by ii

    If max_cycle modulo by ii is greater than 0:
        Set stage_count to stage_count plus 1
    End If

    Return stage_count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Collects the node IDs that belong to a single pipeline stage. After modulo collapse, a node's stage is determined by its original (pre-modulo) cycle divided by II - which is preserved in the entry's offset 8 by callers who supply unmodulo'd schedules, or computable directly when offset 8 still holds the original. Used by software_pipeline to assemble PipelineStage records.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterate every schedule entry, divide its cycle (offset 8) by ii to determine its stage, and append the node ID (offset 0) to the result List when it matches stage_number. Returns a fresh List of node IDs.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_stage_operations" that takes schedule as Integer, stage_number as Integer, ii as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extract operations in specified stage
    Let stage_ops be proc create from List

    Let entry_count be proc length from List with schedule

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with schedule, i
        Let cycle be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8

        Note: Check if operation belongs to this stage
        Let op_stage be cycle divided by ii

        If op_stage is equal to stage_number:
            Let node be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 0
            proc append from List with stage_ops, node
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return stage_ops
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for the canonical ResourceConstraints used when no architecture-specific override is supplied. Encodes the wide-issue baseline (2 mem ports, 4 ALU ports, 1 control port) that matches modern x86_64 cores. Installs the standard latency table: Load 100, Store 1, Add/Sub 1, Multiply 4, Divide 8, MatrixMultiply 50, VectorDot 10.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Construct ResourceConstraints with the four issue-width fields.
2. Create the latency Dict.
3. Populate via repeated proc set from Dict using OpKind integer literals (40=Load, 41=Store, 0=Add, 1=Sub, 2=Mul, 3=Div, 6=MatrixMultiply, 12=VectorDot) as keys.
4. Wire the Dict into constraints.instruction_latencies and return.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_default_constraints" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Note: Create default resource constraints

    Let constraints be a value of type ResourceConstraints with
        max_memory_ops as 2,
        max_arithmetic_ops as 4,
        max_control_ops as 1,
        instruction_latencies as 0

    Note: Create latency map
    Let latencies be proc create from Dict

    Note: Memory ops
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 40, 100 Note: Load = 100 cycles
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 41, 1 Note: Store = 1 cycle

    Note: Arithmetic ops
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 0, 1 Note: Add = 1 cycle
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 1, 1 Note: Subtract = 1 cycle
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 2, 4 Note: Multiply = 4 cycles
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 3, 8 Note: Divide = 8 cycles

    Note: Linear algebra ops
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 6, 50 Note: MatrixMultiply = 50 cycles
    proc set from Dict with latencies, 12, 10 Note: VectorDot = 10 cycles

    Set constraints.instruction_latencies to latencies

    Return constraints
End Process
